%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
## Human-, LLM- and GIT-fiendly Notebook Format
We silently introduced a new version of `.wln` notebook format. The structure is minimal, and easy to read and parse by people and machines, but most importantly, it solves issue with versioning systems being unable to correctly identify the diferences 

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Type: Input
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
.md

:----:Notebook:---:
Quick: true
:-----------------:

:-----:Cells:-----:
Type: Input
:-----------------:
1+1

:-----------------:
Type: Output
:-----------------:
2

:---:EndOfCells:--:

:-:EndOfNotebook:-:

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Props:
  Hidden: true
Type: Input
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
.md
It looks like YAML in headers and was definitely inspired by it. After the coresponding separators the data can be any valid Wolfram Language expression.

:::note
We will never drop the support of the older version of `.wln` format. It costs 0 efforts to maintain the backward compatibillity, since it is just input form of `Association` data structure.
:::

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Display: markdown
Type: Output
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
It looks like YAML in headers and was definitely inspired by it. After the coresponding separators the data can be any valid Wolfram Language expression.

:::note
We will never drop the support of the older version of `.wln` format. It costs 0 efforts to maintain the backward compatibillity, since it is just input form of `Association` data structure.
:::

